  <TR><TD BGCOLOR="#fff5ba" WIDTH="150"><B>Procedural History</B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD ALIGN="left" WIDTH="150">The matter went before the Board of Tax<BR ALIGN='left'/>Appeals upon the question whether the<BR ALIGN='left'/>Commissioner ruled rightly in respect of<BR ALIGN='left'/>this taxable gain. Both parties<BR ALIGN='left'/>proceeded upon the view that there had<BR ALIGN='left'/>been reorganization. Of its own motion,<BR ALIGN='left'/>the Board questioned and denied the<BR ALIGN='left'/>existence of one. It then ruled that the<BR ALIGN='left'/>corporation had realized taxable gain<BR ALIGN='left'/>amounting to the difference between cost<BR ALIGN='left'/>of the property transferred and the cash<BR ALIGN='left'/>received plus the value of the 18,000<BR ALIGN='left'/>shares — $712,195.90.\n\nThe Circuit<BR ALIGN='left'/>Court of Appeals found there was<BR ALIGN='left'/>reorganization within the statute and<BR ALIGN='left'/>reversed the Board. It 383*383 concluded<BR ALIGN='left'/>that the words &quot;the acquisition by one<BR ALIGN='left'/>corporation of .. . substantially all<BR ALIGN='left'/>the property of another corporation&quot;<BR ALIGN='left'/>plainly include the transaction under<BR ALIGN='left'/>consideration. Also that Clause (B), §<BR ALIGN='left'/>112 (i) (1), first introduced by Revenue<BR ALIGN='left'/>Act of 1924, and continued in later<BR ALIGN='left'/>statutes, did not narrow the scope of<BR ALIGN='left'/>Clause (A). Further, that reorganization<BR ALIGN='left'/>was not dependent upon dissolution by<BR ALIGN='left'/>the conveying corporation. And finally,<BR ALIGN='left'/>that its conclusions find support in<BR ALIGN='left'/>Treasury regulations long in force.</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
>]
